entry.title: Roll src/third_party/googletest/src/ af29db7ec..76bb2afb8 (375 commits)
entry.content:
This roll includes several fixes needed to unblock the automated roll.

In particular, the biggest change is disabling Abseil support in

GoogleTest: GoogleTest has switched to using Abseil flags when

GTEST_HAS_ABSL is set, which is incompatible with Chrome. For Chrome,

the main impact of disabling Abseil support is losing the pretty printer

for absl::variant; however, Chrome plans to switch to std::variant once

the codegen issues are fixed.



Unfortunately, this also requires suppressing GN check for GoogleTest

to prevent errors from false positives, since GN does not understand

conditional includes and does not realize that the Abseil flags headers

are not actually included.



https://chromium.googlesource.com/external/github.com/google/googletest.git/+log/af29db7ec28d..76bb2afb8b52



$ git log af29db7ec..76bb2afb8 --date=short --no-merges --format='%ad %ae %s'

2023-11-27 absl-team Implement `testing::Rethrow` to throw exceptions more easily via `std::exception_ptr`

2023-10-26 absl-team Export gmock-spec-builders.

entry.title: Prefetch weight files before loading on-device ML model
entry.content:
This attempts to prefetch the weight files from disk when loading the

model, which can improve performance quite a bit when the weights are

not in the file cache. The weight files for the ML model can be >1 GB,

so reading from disk is a significant piece of startup time.



When testing on Linux, using POSIX_FADV_SEQUENTIAL gives much better

perf than WILLNEED. A follow up patch will add the ability to do this

in PreReadFile.



On my Windows desktop this improves loading time when the file is not

cached by about 500ms. Linux and Mac also have similar magnitude of

improvement.

entry.title: Only support local paths for path validation.
entry.content:
It is unsafe to try and validate a running executable that is

located on a network share, so return an error code if this

is attempted.



In addition, this CL adds additional error values if it is not

possible to determine the path of the executable.



This should make diagnosing errors easier going forward, and

make path validation more reliable.



This does not change validation of existing data so will not

affect decrypt operations, only encryption.



Unfortunately, it is non-trivial to automate tests for these

checks so they have been tested locally by running manual tests

from a network share.



Future CLs will wire this support into //src/chrome.

entry.content:
This accounts for two unusual behaviors on certain automotive devices, caused by certain OEM implementations.



(1) Certain auto devices set the status bar at the bottom, labeling the inset in statusBars() and systemBars(), but not in navigationBars(). Checking bottom in systemBars() should be overall more reliable, since systemBars() includes navigationBars().

entry.title: webauthn: pull the EnclaveManager state machine out.
entry.content:
When the primary user changes, the state machine should stop

immediately. Otherwise, if it continues, it could end up performing

actions on the wrong user account. While the account changing in the

middle of an action will be very rare, it is possible, esp if some

network service is being slow.



However, simply moving the state machine back to the idle state isn't

sufficient because Events from the previous execution might still be

inbound and need to be cleaned up. Each state could check an

`is_doomed_` flag and handle the clean up, but that seems fragile.



Instead, we want to use the `WeakPtr`s which are used with every Event.

That means that we need to destroy the state machine, but we don't want

to destroy the whole EnclaveManager. Thus the state machine needs to be

its own object.



Then, if the user account changes, we can simply delete the state

machine object and the `WeakPtr`s will take care of cleaning up any

in-flight Events.

entry.title: [OBC] Update garbage collection to prefer domain cookies
entry.content:
This CL implements origin-bound cookies' domain garbage collection

behavior. Primarily that domain cookies should be evicted before

host only cookies for a given {priority, secureness} tuple. E.x.:

A {medium, non-secure} domain cookies should be evicted before a

{medium, non-secure} host cookie.



This new eviction behavior is only active when at least one portion

of OBC is active: scheme binding or port binding. Otherwise the existing

eviction algorithm is used. I.e.: When OBC is off we keep the

pre-existing behavior.



When scheme binding is active, the eviction algorithm will now consider a secure cookie to be one that:

* Has the secure attribute.

* Was set by a secure scheme.



To show that priority based eviction behavior hasn't changed this CL

updates the existing tests to run for all possible OBC states which

requires some minor test adjustments in order to properly support OBC.



It is intentional that the new eviction algorithm still considers both

secure and non-secure cookies for the same key. This is because

splitting the cookie store by secureness is out of scope of the initial

OBC design.



This CL does not update global evictions, that will be handled in a

later change.
